00:17:02.050 --> 00:17:04.589
pictures. How do
you reconcile that.

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:08.600
&gt;&gt; Moose: Well, I'm probably not the best
person to ask because

00:17:08.600 --> 00:17:10.750
I'm kind of flippant about the whole thing.
To be

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:13.600
serious with you, when you buy my print, I'll
sign it because

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:15.500
people want me to, but I don't think my name
is that

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:18.449
important. It's the image that's important.
So

00:17:18.449 --> 00:17:20.810
copyright. Yeah, it's a very legal thing that
we have in

00:17:20.810 --> 00:17:24.880
this country. Protects our intellectual properties.
And

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:27.050
that's okay. And if you're going to take my
photograph

00:17:27.050 --> 00:17:30.100
and use it for a commercial purpose in which
you're going

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:33.120
to sell a product and you do it without asking
me, we're

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:35.740
going to have issues. The rest of the time,
personally, I

00:17:35.740 --> 00:17:38.050
think life is too short to worry about it.
Yeah,

00:17:38.050 --> 00:17:40.490
everything is copyrighted. And that's just
to avoid the

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:44.920
hassle if it ever does get stolen, having
to deal with

00:17:44.920 --> 00:17:46.990
courts. Because as soon as I'm not spending
time behind

00:17:46.990 --> 00:17:50.870
my camera, I'm not only not happy, I'm not
making money.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:52.720
So I don't worry about it. A lot of people
seem to worry

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:56.179
about copyright. And I think there's more
important

00:17:56.179 --> 00:17:58.299
issues we need to worry about than copyrighting
our

00:17:58.299 --> 00:18:01.630
images and enforcing it. That's my two cents
worth.

00:18:01.630 --> 00:18:05.851
It's kind of flippant, but it's just I don't
care. For

00:18:05.851 --> 00:18:09.270
lack of better terms. I mean, you got to understand
--

00:18:09.270 --> 00:18:12.910
I've seen it all. In our 31 years, Sharon
and I have seen it all.

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:15.600
It happens at least once a quarter. Somebody
will take

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:18.740
one of my images. You got to realize it's
a 90K file on

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:21.950
that website. And they print it out 8 x 10
and they mail

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:23.710
it to me and say, "can you sign it and send
it back to

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:27.049
me?" I'm like all I see these big squares
on a piece of

00:18:27.049 --> 00:18:30.900
paper. I can't even tell what the hell the
thing is. Do

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:33.460
you realize not only is it this look horrible,
you like

00:18:33.460 --> 00:18:37.120
stole my image. [laughter] So you just can't
worry about those

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:40.410
things. Life is too short. They mean well
and bless the

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:44.031
fans. But what they're doing is simply illegal.
Life

00:18:44.031 --> 00:18:48.660
goes on. All right. Let's talk a little bit
about

00:18:48.660 --> 00:18:51.360
critters. That's what everybody wants to hear
about. No

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:54.600
matter what you see me doing, I'm still a
wildlife

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:57.620
photographer. I always will be. Most of my
work is with

00:18:57.620 --> 00:18:59.990
threatened and endangered critters. What does
that mean?

00:18:59.990 --> 00:19:03.530
These are critters that are about to be extinct.
Most of

00:19:03.530 --> 00:19:06.290
the time that status of threatened and endangered
is a political one,

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:09.640
not biological. If it was biological, we'd
have a whole

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:12.540
lot more on that list and be more concerned
about them

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:17.220
probably. I have 7 species in my files that
are extinct.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:21.010
As in you can't see them no more. They're
gone. And to

00:19:21.010 --> 00:19:24.130
me, that is absolutely criminal; that in my
own lifetime, in

00:19:24.130 --> 00:19:26.710
the state of California, where I'm native
that they are

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:29.220
gone. You cannot go out and find them and
see them.

00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:32.560
Because it's not really ours. It was handed
down to us

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:34.220
and I think it's our responsibility to hand
it to the

00:19:34.220 --> 00:19:37.220
next generation. And I have no doubt that
I'm kind of

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:41.290
preaching to the choir here. I understand
that. But you

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:44.150
have the ability, three different mechanisms,
to put the

00:19:44.150 --> 00:19:47.169
word out there in very many different ways
that we should

00:19:47.169 --> 00:20:42.169
care about this wild heritage.

00:20:42.169 --> 00:21:36.140
[silence]

00:21:36.140 --> 00:22:30.110
[Applause]

00:22:30.110 --> 00:23:26.169
&gt;&gt; Moose: So a real common question is how
do you get those

00:23:26.169 --> 00:23:29.702
pictures? It's a great question. Very valid
when it

00:23:29.702 --> 00:23:32.670
comes to wildlife photography. That's why
I wrote a 400

00:23:32.670 --> 00:23:35.690
page book to try to answer that question how
do you take

00:23:35.690 --> 00:23:39.000
these pictures. It's not like there's a recipe
that I can

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:44.990
provide you that can just instantly make things
happen. What I can do is try to give you insight,

00:23:44.990 --> 00:23:49.130
hope and the possibility that you can do it
as well. Anybody can do

00:23:49.130 --> 00:23:52.809
this. This is not a special person kind of
pursuit. It just

00:23:52.809 --> 00:23:57.080
takes a big heart. So the way I try to answer
that

00:23:57.080 --> 00:23:58.650
question how do you do it is just tell you
some stories

00:23:58.650 --> 00:24:01.790
about how I was fortunate enough to be able
to do it. I actually

00:24:01.790 --> 00:24:06.040
started off with this little bird here called
Least Bell's Vireo. When I started

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:09.549
working with them back in '80 and '81, there
was about 130

00:24:09.549 --> 00:24:14.271
on the planet. That was entire world population.
This

00:24:14.271 --> 00:24:17.211
particular -- I've always had this sixth sense.
I can

00:24:17.211 --> 00:24:22.490
find bird nests. I've always been able to.
It's not like a challenge. I can, like a heat

00:24:22.490 --> 00:24:25.809
seeking missile, just
find them. Foresters hired me to go out and

00:24:25.809 --> 00:24:28.240
find these guys. I
they needed me to survey them. So the deal

00:24:28.240 --> 00:24:32.490
was they provided
me a vehicle and access the place in the morning.

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:34.539
I
found the nest. The afternoon was mine to

00:24:34.539 --> 00:24:37.610
photograph them.
This photograph was here kind of start the

00:24:37.610 --> 00:24:43.730
whole thing.
In that in April of '83, California, Outdoor

00:24:43.730 --> 00:24:46.920
California,
a local magazine put out by our DFG here,

00:24:46.920 --> 00:24:50.799
ran this article and these
photographs. This is truly kind of an artsy

00:24:50.799 --> 00:24:54.450
fartsy
photograph not what most scientists are looking

00:24:54.450 --> 00:24:58.070
for. In
the article, I talked about this bird and

00:24:58.070 --> 00:25:01.630
where it was. There
were two gentlemen down in southern California,

00:25:01.630 --> 00:25:04.441
in Oceanside.
They walk together every morning. And they

00:25:04.441 --> 00:25:07.299
saw
these -- you can really especially hear them

00:25:07.299 --> 00:25:10.960
in the early spring
when the males come back from South America

00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:13.200
and they
always wondered what they were. Gentleman

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:15.230
had my
magazine, came to his friend's house knocked

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:18.190
the door and said “hey I
know what those birds are”. They go, “really”.

00:25:18.190 --> 00:25:21.039
He showed
him the article. And he goes “Wow, you know

00:25:21.039 --> 00:25:24.300
what? That place we see them
down, that piece of riparian forest right

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:27.130
there, they are actually bulldozing it today.”
So they got on

00:25:27.130 --> 00:25:31.280
the phone, called Fish and Wildlife Service
and actually told them the story. And there's

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:34.050
a little clause in our
Endangered Species Act, kind of a big loophole

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:36.571
about destroying stuff when things first get
listed. Still

00:25:36.571 --> 00:25:40.270
hasn't been closed. Anyway, they did stop
it. And

00:25:40.270 --> 00:25:42.520
I've been credited from saving the species
from

00:25:42.520 --> 00:25:47.800
extinction. That's how I started my career.
Kind of a

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:52.120
tease of what's possible with just a photograph.
Now, I do have

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:55.580
my favorite critters. There's no doubt to
it. Kind of

00:25:55.580 --> 00:25:58.531
obvious why. My brothers in the north and
I, we spend a lot of time

00:25:58.531 --> 00:26:01.700
together. They're very unique. They're very
curious.

00:26:01.700 --> 00:26:06.720
For example, that big rack. That's a big giant
radar

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:08.061
dish. And they use those big ears and they
move them

00:26:08.061 --> 00:26:10.320
around inside that. They're listening for
one thing and

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:14.550
that' females moaning in fall for rut. That's
all that big rack

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:18.870
is for is to hear those moans from a long
distance. So

00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:21.039
that kind of trivia has always driven me to
go out and

00:26:21.039 --> 00:26:26.370
find out more answers. You know, the polar
bear. It's an

00:26:26.370 --> 00:26:29.750
iconic animal which it's kind of sad to see
what's in the

00:26:29.750 --> 00:26:31.809
press because most of it's not accurate about
this

00:26:31.809 --> 00:26:36.110
information. The time we were up there photographing,
this is off of Alaska. I refuse to go do

00:26:36.110 --> 00:26:41.590
them in Hudson bay. This is off the Beaufort
Sea in Alaska. And there was a female that

00:26:41.590 --> 00:26:44.240
drowned
because her ice pack which a couple of years

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:50.860
before. So
this was taken in 2003, so in 2001, the ice

00:26:50.860 --> 00:26:54.929
pack was
about 150 yards offshore. But at this point,

00:26:54.929 --> 00:26:59.909
at this year, it was two miles
offshore. She drowned trying to get back in.

00:26:59.909 --> 00:27:02.929
So they
are getting hit by the thing called climate

00:27:02.929 --> 00:27:07.070
change. And
that is really kind of -- really changed a

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:08.710
lot of things
that Sharon and I do for the simple reason

00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:11.809
that a lot of
the places we have tried to preserve over

00:27:11.809 --> 00:27:14.230
our three
decades of work in California. A These little

00:27:14.230 --> 00:27:17.481
islands of habitat
people don't think about much but as the climate

00:27:17.481 --> 00:27:19.630
changes, but
these little islands of habitat the endangered

00:27:19.630 --> 00:27:22.170
species called home now it won't be there
anymore.

00:27:22.170 --> 00:27:26.340
Climate change will completely change it and
they'll blink out. Blink out is

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:31.860
kind of a hopeful term for extinction. So
like Fresno Kangaroo Rat. You're not going

00:27:31.860 --> 00:27:35.559
to see them anywhere else but
there. It's gone. Hasn't been seen since the

00:27:35.559 --> 00:27:40.520
photograph
was taken in 87. So extinct. Can't find it.

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:43.070
They've
been trying hard. So that's one thing that

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:46.610
we're trying to do
with our mission is to not only, I get these

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:50.010
phone calls.
Not only really more phone calls, it's usually

00:27:50.010 --> 00:27:53.820
text. It's amazing how it
evolved. It used to be phone calls. Then,

00:27:53.820 --> 00:27:57.120
it got faxes.
Then it got to be e-mails and now it's text.

00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:59.460
I get this
message. “Can you show up. We found this.

00:27:59.460 --> 00:28:02.539
We need you to
photograph it”. And I do that quite a bit.

00:28:02.539 --> 00:28:04.659
And that's
where the photographic expertise comes in.

00:28:04.659 --> 00:28:08.730
You have to
bring in the camera and tell the story not

00:28:08.730 --> 00:28:10.630
only
biologically and historically correct but

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:15.360
technically and
communicatively very effective. So I just

00:28:15.360 --> 00:28:17.470
want to tell
you about this one story and how things kind

00:28:17.470 --> 00:28:20.161
of evolved.
It's how wildlife photography in my book it

00:28:20.161 --> 00:28:24.780
should work and how it's always worked for
us. I work with biologists extensively. I

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:28.870
have since
day one. They are the keepers to the keys

00:28:28.870 --> 00:28:32.260
of the
kingdom. They are the ones that -- in seriousness,

00:28:32.260 --> 00:28:35.230
I
don't have time to go out and sit somewhere

00:28:35.230 --> 00:28:38.700
and wait for
the things to happen. It's just -- in a business

00:28:38.700 --> 00:28:41.559
sense,
that's not a good business plan. So I've been

00:28:41.559 --> 00:28:43.270
very
fortunate. Biologists are saying, "hey, we're

00:28:43.270 --> 00:28:46.030
seeing it
here now. Can you photograph it here now?"

00:28:46.030 --> 00:28:49.470
And that's what
I've been doing for 30 years. So in this case,

00:28:49.470 --> 00:28:53.050
UAF --
University of Alaska, Fairbanks, doing a lot

00:28:53.050 --> 00:28:55.250
of work as
you might imagine on this thing called climate

00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:58.900
change. But they don't do
it in a conventional way. They do it very

00:28:58.900 --> 00:29:01.961
old-fashioned
way. Because of the the head prof there. He's

00:29:01.961 --> 00:29:06.490
kind of
old-fashioned. So we had a Ph. D. Candidate,

00:29:06.490 --> 00:29:10.809
Hayley, and she went
around. 53 years ago, this biologist went

00:29:10.809 --> 00:29:13.770
around and
sampled all the Collared Pika which you see

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:18.260
on the screen
now. He sampled the entire world population

00:29:18.260 --> 00:29:22.440
which is down
in Canada all the way up into Alaska and sample

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:28.090
means [makes shotgun noises]
okay? Take a skin, do the skulls, basic sampling

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:31.961
which is
what science has been doing for eons. Science

00:29:31.961 --> 00:29:34.640
is as
science should be -- it's a very regimented,

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:39.570
formula
oriented, this is my hypothesis, can I prove

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:42.670
it scenario.
So she went back with this incredible sample

00:29:42.670 --> 00:29:46.679
from 53 years ago
went back and did it all again. And what she

00:29:46.679 --> 00:29:50.440
found
out, was two things. In the entire population

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:55.660
of Collared Pikas, one thing is a little bone
in the skull had changed. The entire

00:29:55.660 --> 00:29:58.039
population. They don't have fax. They don't
have

00:29:58.039 --> 00:30:00.429
e-mail. They don't have a way of saying 'okay
everybody, change this

00:30:00.429 --> 00:30:03.970
bone in your skull to be this long'. They
evolved within 50

00:30:03.970 --> 00:30:09.830
years this one thing. At the same time, they
live at a very special

00:30:09.830 --> 00:30:14.630
altitude and that's because, they're active
365. So right now in their world,

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:19.659
it's 24/7 darkness and it's about minus 30
degrees plus or

00:30:19.659 --> 00:30:23.710
minus 5. And so, they need this density of
snow to keep

00:30:23.710 --> 00:30:27.360
them going. Well, that density of snow isn't
the same at

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:30.059
that same altitude. So the entire population,
they all

00:30:30.059 --> 00:30:34.429
moved up the slope. They all moved up the
slope. This is

00:30:34.429 --> 00:30:38.260
direct because of the change in the climate.
They don't

00:30:38.260 --> 00:30:42.150
have, in the summer time, where they were,
the warmth they

00:30:42.150 --> 00:30:46.630
need to grow the forearms they have to grab.
And what they do.

00:30:46.630 --> 00:30:49.630
This is Number 6 and he was a character. Now,
a Collared Pika

00:30:49.630 --> 00:30:53.240
is about the size of tennis ball. They're
little guys,

00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:57.700
all right? And they live on talus slopes . Talus
slopes are what you see a lot

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:02.600
in the Sierra. It's where you have all that
border of boulders borders and all those rocks

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:05.179
and
rubble on the side of a slope. That's a talus

00:31:05.179 --> 00:31:06.980
slope and
they live in that. And they bounce around

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:09.740
like a tennis
ball on these rocks. They're just these dynamos

00:31:09.740 --> 00:31:14.029
going every which way, in part so they don't
get preyed upon. They have

00:31:14.029 --> 00:31:16.880
no defenses. They can't like scare anything.
They're

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:20.039
commonly called rock rabbits. They're cute.
They're

00:31:20.039 --> 00:31:23.430
fuzzy. They go oink, oink. That's the noise
they make.

00:31:23.430 --> 00:31:26.460
They're just one of a kind, kind of critters.
We have the American

00:31:26.460 --> 00:31:30.620
Pika down here. It should be listed. It's
now in such a

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:33.440
peril, they're thinking about listing it as
threatened. And this is the thing called Collared

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:37.820
Pika, which
is the far reaches of North America. Well,

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:41.280
Number 6 -- what
he's doing here is what they normally do in

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:43.760
the summer
time. They're constantly going out to get

00:31:43.760 --> 00:31:47.600
greeneries and bringing through these rocks.
They're constantly creating hay pails, hay

00:31:47.600 --> 00:31:53.809
piles just like you might think
a farmer might do. And this is what it looks

00:31:53.809 --> 00:31:57.160
like Number 6
jumping the Grand Canyon. Probably, maybe

00:31:57.160 --> 00:32:01.880
18, 20 inches and this
photograph in print form is in everything

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:05.600
from Harvard and
Smithsonian and Yale. It's actually around

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.409
the globe, these prints
have gone out because it's kind of like what

00:32:09.409 --> 00:32:12.471
they use as
a mascot to talk about climate warming. Because

00:32:12.471 --> 00:32:16.450
what's
happening with that change in altitude -- they

00:32:16.450 --> 00:32:19.010
only have
so much mountain they go to and then there

00:32:19.010 --> 00:32:22.429
ain't no more.
That's the issue. On this particular mountain

00:32:22.429 --> 00:32:26.080
where Number
6 lived -- it was a small colony up in the

00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:30.020
Alaska range
and there's probably I'm going to say 33,

00:32:30.020 --> 00:32:34.710
36 Collared Pika
on this entire slope. They only had about

00:32:34.710 --> 00:32:38.520
another 40 feet, vertical
feet to go up and then there was just sky.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:41.659
And there's
no more place for them to go. So we worked

00:32:41.659 --> 00:32:45.890
on this project. This was one of the projects
Like most of my projects, they're all self-funded.

00:32:45.890 --> 00:32:48.710
There's no funding for these projects. The
biologists

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:54.460
need this documentation. Their hands are full.
They're busy doing what they do in their research.

00:32:54.460 --> 00:32:57.450
So
it's up to me to get not only the photographs

00:32:57.450 --> 00:33:01.140
but
anecdotal evidence. As a photographer, I'm

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:03.240
not seeing
things over and over again and I'm not recording

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:06.130
that so
it's a one time thing so it's called anecdotal

00:33:06.130 --> 00:33:09.550
even
though it's a photograph that's part of the

00:33:09.550 --> 00:33:12.080
process. So
I'm out there not only to make the picture

00:33:12.080 --> 00:33:15.090
record all
this information, but then it's my goal to

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:17.429
bring that
story back. That's the whole goal. Because

00:33:17.429 --> 00:33:21.070
how many
people here have heard of a Collared Pika

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:25.640
before? That's my
point. It's just not known, not seen. Well,

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:27.501
this
project we worked on for about ten days. We

00:33:27.501 --> 00:33:33.360
is my youngest son
Jake and myself. So Link -- the head prof

00:33:33.360 --> 00:33:36.880
said, "hey,
we're going to go after a critter that is

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:39.390
in worse shape
than the Collared Pika up there." And I said,

00:33:39.390 --> 00:33:42.070
"really?" He goes,
"yeah." So two years ago, we started planning

00:33:42.070 --> 00:33:48.310
this three week trip up the Haul Road
Many people have seen the Haul Road trucker

00:33:48.310 --> 00:33:53.880
thing on Discovery. It's
horrible. Anyway, this is the Haul Road, okay?

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:58.130
It's an
amazing transportation corridor up through

00:33:58.130 --> 00:34:01.030
the arctic up
to the Beaufort Arctic Ocean and people know

00:34:01.030 --> 00:34:05.789
it basically because of the
trucks that go back and forth. It's just,

00:34:05.789 --> 00:34:09.520
you know, it's
very inviting kind of place. That's a joke

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:15.929
folks. It's
okay. [laughter] So we landed in Fairbanks.

00:34:15.929 --> 00:34:20.230
And at Fairbanks we
sat there and basically after a year of planning

00:34:20.230 --> 00:34:23.109
our
three week trip, because of political reasons

00:34:23.109 --> 00:34:25.919
more than
anything else, got down to three days. So

00:34:25.919 --> 00:34:29.500
all we had to
do was three days of work. So we got on the

00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:33.079
truck. And
we drove. We went north of the Yukon river.

00:34:33.079 --> 00:34:35.139
And that's
important because what we're going to go find

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:39.010
is only
found north of the Yukon river now. And we

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:41.720
kept on going
up to a place called Slope Mountain. It's

00:34:41.720 --> 00:34:45.049
about a
12-hour drive up the Haul Road which in itself

00:34:45.049 --> 00:34:48.940
is a crazy
amazing experience. What you see up there

00:34:48.940 --> 00:34:52.539
is just
unbelievable. It's not barren by any stretch

00:34:52.539 --> 00:34:55.489
of
imagination. It's full of life. Full of activity

00:34:55.489 --> 00:34:58.479
and
it's strategy for the critters and plants

00:34:58.479 --> 00:35:01.759
to survive in
this environment is really just a little bit

00:35:01.759 --> 00:35:04.670
more than
the mind can comprehend that they do survive

00:35:04.670 --> 00:35:08.069
in such
incredible, spectacular way. So we kept on

00:35:08.069 --> 00:35:12.240
going up. And we are going
to the place that literally has just been

00:35:12.240 --> 00:35:15.530
named on
the USGS the week after we came back. And

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:19.869
it's called Slope Mountain. You ever been
to Alaska? There's got to be 1,000 Slope Mountains.

00:35:19.869 --> 00:35:22.459
I
don't know why they can't get past that name.

00:35:22.459 --> 00:35:24.559
I can tell
you Slope Mountain. You can Google it, ha

00:35:24.559 --> 00:35:27.869
Google it, and you'll find
all these spots and you'll never know where

00:35:27.869 --> 00:35:30.390
I was.
That's kind of the cool thing. Maybe that's

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:32.710
why I do it.
All the hunters I know say, “I went to Slope

00:35:32.710 --> 00:35:38.319
Mountain.” "Uh, which
one?" And so, we got up there. And this is

00:35:38.319 --> 00:35:40.509
what we
found when we got up to Slope Mountain. Slope

00:35:40.509 --> 00:35:43.609
Mountain
is there in the fog and the rain. This is

00:35:43.609 --> 00:35:49.229
late July.
Looking through that fog is the arctic plain.

00:35:49.229 --> 00:35:53.569
It's an
amazing location. You know, you're talking

00:35:53.569 --> 00:35:56.410
about
everything from wolves and grizzly bears and

00:35:56.410 --> 00:36:01.009
caribou to
Siberian birds that are over summering in

00:36:01.009 --> 00:36:06.849
Alaska. Now, one of
the first things that I was told about this

00:36:06.849 --> 00:36:11.940
critter in
when I Link first sent it to me, he said,

00:36:11.940 --> 00:36:15.130
“it's never been
photographed before”. I said, “Say, what?”

00:36:15.130 --> 00:36:18.559
He said, “Well, there's one picture”.
I said

00:36:18.559 --> 00:36:23.940
“okay”. He said, "it's a Sarah Palin story.
OK? There you go.” You all

00:36:23.940 --> 00:36:27.259
start laughing right off the bat. Anyway,
they decided

00:36:27.259 --> 00:36:30.140
they need to have a official ground hog for
Alaska

00:36:30.140 --> 00:36:35.089
Groundhog Day and there's four ground hog
species in Alaska

00:36:35.089 --> 00:36:37.049
so off they went on a goose chase to see which
one was

00:36:37.049 --> 00:36:43.130
the most charismatic, photographic looking
marmot, ground hog, for Groundhog Day. It

00:36:43.130 --> 00:36:45.289
only gets worse from there so I'm going to
stop. But

00:36:45.289 --> 00:36:47.460
this one guy went up there and he went with
the biologist

00:36:47.460 --> 00:36:53.729
I'm working with. He put his Coolpix onto
a spotting scope, and shot through the fog

00:36:53.729 --> 00:36:56.160
and got this picture. So prior to us, that
