So that was part of the challenge. And then,
there really wasn't much known about the Alaska

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:06.309
marmot.
Still isn't. A lot of the basics just aren't

00:37:06.309 --> 00:37:09.749
there. So
that truck was clean. That is the Alaska pipeline

00:37:09.749 --> 00:37:13.459
behind
us as we head up and over. The Alaskan pipeline

00:37:13.459 --> 00:37:19.700
is an amazing corridor.
Engineering wise, biological wise; the misinformation

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:24.220
about
that whole thing still boggles my mind. But

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:29.640
that Slope
Mountain once the fog and clouds disappear.

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:32.799
And we're
going to climb that thing. And we have to

00:37:32.799 --> 00:37:36.309
climb it when
it's sunny, because that's the only time these

00:37:36.309 --> 00:37:39.969
guys
are out. Well, that evening and that evening

00:37:39.969 --> 00:37:43.829
being about
12 p.m., 1 a.m., you can still see the sun

00:37:43.829 --> 00:37:47.819
on the slope.
We were good. All is fine. We checked out

00:37:47.819 --> 00:37:51.140
the creek
because that creek there we had to get our

00:37:51.140 --> 00:37:55.450
stuff across.
We actually put a rubber raft on that creek

00:37:55.450 --> 00:37:57.650
with a rope
that we could pull ourselves across to get

00:37:57.650 --> 00:38:00.729
from this side
to the other side to get up the slope. We

00:38:00.729 --> 00:38:05.569
had permission by Alaska to camp right there
by the pipeline.

00:38:05.569 --> 00:38:07.950
There's our rubber rope. That's where we're
camping.

00:38:07.950 --> 00:38:11.759
It's not one of those warm, cozy Alaska lodges
that you

00:38:11.759 --> 00:38:15.229
would think of. It is the basic kind of biological
camp.

00:38:15.229 --> 00:38:19.660
The biggest tent is the food/animal prep tent.
And from

00:38:19.660 --> 00:38:24.720
there we just went across. As you can see
it's raining

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:28.209
again. It was pouring. Didn't stop. We had
three days

00:38:28.209 --> 00:38:31.499
to get out and do this. And I had to have
sun for these

00:38:31.499 --> 00:38:36.511
guys to show up. It was just horrible. Get
out of the

00:38:36.511 --> 00:38:40.779
tent that morning, have our cold pancakes
with bacon.

00:38:40.779 --> 00:38:44.960
And we three days -- off you go. Now, this
is one of

00:38:44.960 --> 00:38:47.460
those -- people asked me if I have done stupid
things in wildlife

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:51.089
photography. This has to be right up at the
top five. This slope

00:38:51.089 --> 00:38:56.839
wasn't just some little walk up a foothill.
And the biologist I'm working with,

00:38:56.839 --> 00:39:00.920
he had tried out for Survivor, the TV show,
and he actually

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:05.700
had won and gotten on there and he was on
that show. But

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:07.920
when they started taping, it said it was going
to take him

00:39:07.920 --> 00:39:11.109
into the season, he bailed out from the show.
This is the guy I'm going

00:39:11.109 --> 00:39:15.400
to follow up the slope, okay? Not smart, okay?
So I've

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:20.810
got the 600 millimeter body on my shoulder.
We're going up this

00:39:20.810 --> 00:39:24.329
slope that's about a 38 percent grade. It's
loose shale.

00:39:24.329 --> 00:39:28.339
We're going up this thing. Mr. Jackrabbit
he's on top in a

00:39:28.339 --> 00:39:31.739
heartbeat. I'm like “Holy--”. And I'm
at the bottom. Take a step ,

00:39:31.739 --> 00:39:35.749
slide back two. Take a step, slide back two.
600 on the back. It's raining my son's going

00:39:35.749 --> 00:39:37.650
up.
And so, the old man is the back. Should never

00:39:37.650 --> 00:39:40.479
have been up this
hill. We go up there and this is what we see.

00:39:40.479 --> 00:39:45.049
I mean,
this is all we're seeing. There's no sun.

00:39:45.049 --> 00:39:47.959
Means there
ain't going to be any critters. But we sat

00:39:47.959 --> 00:39:50.709
there for
five hours in the rain hunched over anyway

00:39:50.709 --> 00:39:55.079
because you
have three days. That's it. Well, they went

00:39:55.079 --> 00:39:57.499
to the very
top and they're kind of shooting was a little

00:39:57.499 --> 00:39:59.250
bit
different than ours and they did manage to

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:02.640
get one
sample. Now, you might be saying and asking

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:06.190
yourself is
it possible it could be going extinct, if

00:40:06.190 --> 00:40:08.549
it's in trouble why would you be shooting
and

00:40:08.549 --> 00:40:12.869
sampling these? Well, it's like anything in
biological

00:40:12.869 --> 00:40:14.910
field. If you don't have answers, it's hard
to figure

00:40:14.910 --> 00:40:18.390
out solutions. And without knowing much about
the

00:40:18.390 --> 00:40:22.900
critters, simple basic thing is what do they
eat? Things

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:26.039
like that. It's hard to make calls about what
needs to

00:40:26.039 --> 00:40:30.609
be done on their behalf. And that's part of
the project.

00:40:30.609 --> 00:40:33.150
And that's one of them. It's not alive any
longer. How

00:40:33.150 --> 00:40:35.619
many have they shot in the entire breadth
of this

00:40:35.619 --> 00:40:38.680
project. I think it's like number 13. It's
not like they're shooting

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:42.019
out millions of them. They take very select
samples from

00:40:42.019 --> 00:40:45.980
select areas. And then, the biology starts.
And the guy

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:50.180
on the right -- he's the the Survivor champion.
And he

00:40:50.180 --> 00:40:54.609
is also the curator of the biggest DNA depository
for

00:40:54.609 --> 00:40:57.390
critters on the planet up at UAF. So his pedigree
for

00:40:57.390 --> 00:41:00.729
knowing this stuff is amazing. And it's a
lot they learn

00:41:00.729 --> 00:41:04.069
from these guys. But it's only so much. They
need to be

00:41:04.069 --> 00:41:06.829
able to sit there and find out what I do best
-- that

00:41:06.829 --> 00:41:11.230
anecdotal evidence. So the next day we went
out and it

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:13.119
was obviously going up that slope wasn't going
to work.

00:41:13.119 --> 00:41:16.910
I can't believe I'm hear to talk about it
anyway. Had to

00:41:16.910 --> 00:41:19.760
find another slope that was easy to egress.
We had only

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:22.049
three days and now we had only two. We had
to find

00:41:22.049 --> 00:41:25.319
critters who would come out. So we went to
another spot.

00:41:25.319 --> 00:41:28.200
Weather still didn't cooperate. This is all
the Alaska

00:41:28.200 --> 00:41:31.259
range which is an absolutely spectacular part
of this

00:41:31.259 --> 00:41:34.710
planet. It's hard to describe the life that
goes on

00:41:34.710 --> 00:41:37.829
here. And the critters aren't what you might
think. The

00:41:37.829 --> 00:41:42.550
caribous, they come in. They do their thing.
They love to follow that pipeline

00:41:42.550 --> 00:41:45.049
because the heat that's generated from it.
Oil is going

00:41:45.049 --> 00:41:48.359
through that the at 10,000 PSI and it's getting
shot down that tube.

00:41:48.359 --> 00:41:51.039
The heat that's generated from that is amazing.
And the

00:41:51.039 --> 00:41:55.509
life that comes around that in the form of
forbs and

00:41:55.509 --> 00:41:58.709
stuff feeds a lot of critters. But they'll
come right up

00:41:58.709 --> 00:42:01.279
and just say hello. They have absolutely no
inhibition

00:42:01.279 --> 00:42:05.420
to us like you might think. And I saw everything
I could

00:42:05.420 --> 00:42:10.269
imagine up there from peregrine falcons and
wolves and grizzly bears and caribou but

00:42:10.269 --> 00:42:12.809
I still hadn't gotten the main critter I was
after. And

00:42:12.809 --> 00:42:17.329
that was the Alaska marmot. And then finally
about an

00:42:17.329 --> 00:42:20.740
hour or, so we got to see our first one. Now,
Alaska

00:42:20.740 --> 00:42:23.690
Marmot -- it's not like the Yellow-bellied
Marmot you might

00:42:23.690 --> 00:42:29.069
see here in the Sierras or up Denali National
Park even. They're

00:42:29.069 --> 00:42:32.930
big hogs, okay? They have been harvested for
food.

00:42:32.930 --> 00:42:35.119
You'll see pictures of them underneath the
wing of a

00:42:35.119 --> 00:42:38.029
Cessna. And they're longer than the wing of
the Cessna is wide.

00:42:38.029 --> 00:42:41.359
They're big things. They're massive. At the
same time,

00:42:41.359 --> 00:42:44.180
they are the longest true hibernators of any
mammal on

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:48.259
the planet. Their period of time above ground
is just

00:42:48.259 --> 00:42:50.700
nothing. And in that period of time like a
lot of

00:42:50.700 --> 00:42:53.190
critters they come up, get fat, make babies
and they go

00:42:53.190 --> 00:42:57.170
back to sleep. You know that's it. Well, so
we got a

00:42:57.170 --> 00:43:00.130
couple clicks of them, but that's it. I'm
sitting on the

00:43:00.130 --> 00:43:03.859
ridge looking. That's what I did for the whole
day.

00:43:03.859 --> 00:43:07.269
Couple pictures. So okay, first one to photograph
the

00:43:07.269 --> 00:43:11.369
marmot. Not enough. So it rained again the
next night.

00:43:11.369 --> 00:43:13.459
And remember I got to have that sunshine.
Sunshine is

00:43:13.459 --> 00:43:16.010
everything. So we had to find another spot.
The next

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:20.799
day, we thought, okay it's starting off with
a good omen. So off we

00:43:20.799 --> 00:43:24.579
went, went up the hill. Went up a different
hill this time and this time we had

00:43:24.579 --> 00:43:27.890
no threat of rain. It rained, it was gone
and we were

00:43:27.890 --> 00:43:30.440
out. And we're in a part of the world even
these

00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:34.569
satellite phones don't want to work. We're
up there at the top curve where there's no

00:43:34.569 --> 00:43:36.630
communication.
There's no way of looking at radar pictures

00:43:36.630 --> 00:43:39.249
to see what
storm fronts are coming in. It's the last

00:43:39.249 --> 00:43:42.160
day; we go for the gusto. So up the hill we
went and

00:43:42.160 --> 00:43:45.469
Jake and I went up to the top of the hill.
This is our

00:43:45.469 --> 00:43:50.309
view. And for three hours, we watch the view.
And just

00:43:50.309 --> 00:43:54.680
watched the view. And watched the view. And
the clock

00:43:54.680 --> 00:43:58.130
is ticking. And the day before four marmots
had been

00:43:58.130 --> 00:44:00.680
seen at this burrow. And we're like okay,
they got to

00:44:00.680 --> 00:44:04.119
come out. So three hours are gone into it.
We watched

00:44:04.119 --> 00:44:06.770
everything. Helicopters going back and forth
watching

00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:10.010
looking at the pipeline, doing its survey
work. We watch

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:14.759
a brand new Camaro go up the Haul Road. This
is a brand

00:44:14.759 --> 00:44:19.519
new, bright yellow, Transformer kind of Camaro,
the probably some military guy just bought

00:44:19.519 --> 00:44:23.319
in Fairbanks and decided
to go for a ride. It had to be destroyed.

00:44:23.319 --> 00:44:26.289
The Haul Road
is these big pebbles and we've lost as many

00:44:26.289 --> 00:44:29.980
as 9 tires on one
trip up this road. So that Camaro was like

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:32.310
the highlight of
entertainment after sitting on a rock for

00:44:32.310 --> 00:44:37.079
three hours.
And then finally, one came out. And had the

00:44:37.079 --> 00:44:40.400
opportunity
of starting to actually do what it is I do

00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:43.800
and that is to
photograph the biology of a critter. That's

00:44:43.800 --> 00:44:46.569
my
specialty. Asking questions in my mind and

00:44:46.569 --> 00:44:49.109
trying to
find it in the view finder to bring back answers

00:44:49.109 --> 00:44:51.630
to
biologists is what I've done for 30 years.

00:44:51.630 --> 00:44:56.130
Now for
critter that sits there and basically hibernates

00:44:56.130 --> 00:45:00.230
most of it's life,
activity is not really what it's striving

00:45:00.230 --> 00:45:03.680
for, okay?
They're like -- it's a simple thing with critters.

00:45:03.680 --> 00:45:06.769
Calories in, calories out. I want to get fat.
Means I

00:45:06.769 --> 00:45:11.529
don't do anything. Well photographically,
can get boring

00:45:11.529 --> 00:45:14.339
real fast, okay? You're sitting there been
sitting on a

00:45:14.339 --> 00:45:17.989
rock. We haven't moved. Haven't moved an inch.
We're stuck because you

00:45:17.989 --> 00:45:21.369
don't know if your movement is going to keep
them from coming out for another five minutes.

00:45:21.369 --> 00:45:24.670
So we're just stuck. No
matter what biological thing is calling on

00:45:24.670 --> 00:45:28.170
us to go find
another rock or anything else, you're stuck.

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:32.049
And then,
they come out and this is what they do. Now,

00:45:32.049 --> 00:45:34.079
as I
typically do, I take a lot of notes. I have

00:45:34.079 --> 00:45:37.690
a GPS in the
camera so it's tagging all my images. That

00:45:37.690 --> 00:45:39.849
information
goes right to the biologists. They can sit

00:45:39.849 --> 00:45:43.190
there and figure out where I was
and with our software digital probing sit

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:45.259
there and
actually -- because I'm using the auto focus--

00:45:45.259 --> 00:45:47.619
know how far
I am physically from that critter. So they

00:45:47.619 --> 00:45:51.859
have that information.
It's carved in stone from EXIF data. But I

00:45:51.859 --> 00:45:55.499
still take a
lot of paper notes. I take a micro-cassette

00:45:55.499 --> 00:46:00.579
recorder. Taking
verbal notes and I'm watching and shooting

00:46:00.579 --> 00:46:04.589
that whole
time. Now, for a critter that has nothing

00:46:04.589 --> 00:46:07.769
known about
it, anything that we saw or we photographed

00:46:07.769 --> 00:46:11.680
was new. It was
like innovative. It was like unbelievable.

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:14.329
So how they
moved across the slope. How the four of them

00:46:14.329 --> 00:46:18.160
interacted was all
important. But really what got to them was,

00:46:18.160 --> 00:46:21.999
I'm shooting this
D3X. It's a 2X on the 600. I'm sitting there

00:46:21.999 --> 00:46:25.359
shooting. That's the burrow.
And after awhile, I simply said, “okay,

00:46:25.359 --> 00:46:28.359
I think I've got
this shot”. So I watch the clouds and I

00:46:28.359 --> 00:46:33.210
watch them. Then I
put the D 3 S on a camera and I shot a video.

00:46:33.210 --> 00:46:37.249
I shot a
total of about four hours of video and the

00:46:37.249 --> 00:46:41.479
big thing was
everything in that video had never been seen

00:46:41.479 --> 00:46:44.740
before.
They had not seen any of this part of it.

00:46:44.740 --> 00:46:46.920
Because
biologists don't have the luxury of time to

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:51.259
just sit and stare at
something. It's long gone from our biology

00:46:51.259 --> 00:46:56.589
and our
system. It's just time and money. It's that

00:46:56.589 --> 00:47:01.059
real simple. I
got here just a simple nine minute clip of

00:47:01.059 --> 00:47:05.150
all that video
I shot. That's because I know at about minute

00:47:05.150 --> 00:47:08.270
30, you going are
all going to start wiggling and going, “Okay,

00:47:08.270 --> 00:47:12.059
time to change the
slide. Time to move”. And this is only nine

00:47:12.059 --> 00:47:16.789
minutes of
my 14 hours on that rock that afternoon. That's

00:47:16.789 --> 00:47:19.000
what I
do. I sit on my ass on a rock and I stare

