you work with, but the marmots -- not knowing
how many

01:00:54.519 --> 01:01:01.479
existed, anything about them -- what was learned
from the

01:01:01.479 --> 01:01:04.839
samples taken that couldn't have been learned
from a live

01:01:04.839 --> 01:01:07.890
capture with the radio collar and a blood
sample and

01:01:07.890 --> 01:01:08.890
fecal sample.

01:01:08.890 --> 01:01:11.619
&gt;&gt; Moose: That's a good question. What could
be learned from

01:01:11.619 --> 01:01:15.539
the -- well first and foremost it's called
money. So a

01:01:15.539 --> 01:01:20.799
live capture. You're talking about minimum
one day 800

01:01:20.799 --> 01:01:26.870
to 2000 dollars one person live capture, okay?
I don't know if

01:01:26.870 --> 01:01:29.349
you know, but money is like tight and no one
gives a

01:01:29.349 --> 01:01:32.299
squat about Alaska marmots. So getting funding
just to

01:01:32.299 --> 01:01:35.002
go out for our three days of survey work to
do was

01:01:35.002 --> 01:01:39.181
impossible to do. That's the first real world
answer to

01:01:39.181 --> 01:01:42.859
that question. And then, the next -- having
a marked

01:01:42.859 --> 01:01:46.019
population works when you have a population
you can

01:01:46.019 --> 01:01:47.941
actually deal with. And you're talking about
critters

01:01:47.941 --> 01:01:50.609
who for basically two and a half months out
of the year,

01:01:50.609 --> 01:01:53.180
other than that you can't get to them. So
that marked

01:01:53.180 --> 01:01:57.239
population isn't going to work. Lastly is
technology. When

01:01:57.239 --> 01:01:59.519
you're working with a critter that's living
in minus 30,

01:01:59.519 --> 01:02:04.380
minus 40, batteries in a portable device that
fits around the neck or implanted

01:02:04.380 --> 01:02:07.400
in the abdomen, we don't have that kind of
viable

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:11.489
technology. So it's a lot of technical issues
as well as

01:02:11.489 --> 01:02:14.859
anything else. John James Adam Audubon. Anybody
know

01:02:14.859 --> 01:02:18.529
about the artist. John James Audubon. Anybody
know who he is? You know he

01:02:18.529 --> 01:02:24.089
shot everything he painted? Okay? It's a lineage
in

01:02:24.089 --> 01:02:27.849
science -- there's a recipe that, if you're
a scientist

01:02:27.849 --> 01:02:29.709
and you have to prove your point, you go,
“I went and

01:02:29.709 --> 01:02:32.950
follow rowed this regimen and this regimen;
this protocol, this protocol” and

01:02:32.950 --> 01:02:34.900
so, if you did all those things and you made
this

01:02:34.900 --> 01:02:41.319
conclusion, then the logic and the facts can't
be argued so that must be accurate.

01:02:41.319 --> 01:02:44.710
So that's part of the science regime as well.
Like I

01:02:44.710 --> 01:02:47.920
said, the number of specimens they have shot
is nothing

01:02:47.920 --> 01:02:51.599
compared to the world population. And in this
day and time,

01:02:51.599 --> 01:02:53.959
it's the only way we're going to get answers
especially probably

01:02:53.959 --> 01:02:57.789
in the period of time we have allotted to
us. Yeah. [female in audience comments off

01:02:57.789 --> 01:03:00.719
mic] I
know. It's a cute little thing that got shot.

01:03:00.719 --> 01:03:04.130
You'd be
surprised how many deer in the eastern Sierras

01:03:04.130 --> 01:03:09.049
who are run over
every year because of our cars and that's

01:03:09.049 --> 01:03:11.880
not even in the
name of science. So it does seem cruel, but

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:15.779
that's the
process. And to be honest with you, if a scientist

01:03:15.779 --> 01:03:17.930
53
years ago had not sampled all those Collared

01:03:17.930 --> 01:03:21.509
Pica, if he
hadn't done that and those bone collections

01:03:21.509 --> 01:03:24.429
weren't in
the Smithsonian, Harvard, Yale, Berkeley.

01:03:24.429 --> 01:03:28.099
If those
specimens weren't here for us to look at,

01:03:28.099 --> 01:03:33.059
there's no way that Hayley could have gone
now and said that bone changed.

01:03:33.059 --> 01:03:37.990
Everybody goes, “and there's proof”. So,
there's the flip

01:03:37.990 --> 01:03:41.519
side too. Without that proof, that whole thing
would not

01:03:41.519 --> 01:03:44.979
have opened up and a whole another study of
science as

01:03:44.979 --> 01:03:49.549
far as climate change would have progressed.
So it's the

01:03:49.549 --> 01:03:52.059
hard facts and then, yeah, I know it's cute
and it's dead,

01:03:52.059 --> 01:03:54.229
but there's a reason.

01:03:54.229 --> 01:04:00.229
&gt;&gt; Male #7: All right. I have two questions.
First one is you

01:04:00.229 --> 01:04:02.919
talk about knowing what the story you want
to tell when

01:04:02.919 --> 01:04:06.239
you take your pictures. How often does your
story

01:04:06.239 --> 01:04:08.079
develop while you're taking the picture while
you're

01:04:08.079 --> 01:04:11.169
looking at the critter and how much is it
before you

01:04:11.169 --> 01:04:13.059
start climbing the mountain you know what
you want to

01:04:13.059 --> 01:04:14.059
shoot.

01:04:14.059 --> 01:04:16.809
&gt;&gt; Moose: That's a a great question. I, first
of all, do all the

01:04:16.809 --> 01:04:20.109
homework I can on anything I'm about to work
on. So I have

01:04:20.109 --> 01:04:23.869
a basic idea about what I want to photograph
and how I

01:04:23.869 --> 01:04:26.169
want to say it. Now, do the photo gods always
provide it

01:04:26.169 --> 01:04:30.200
and does mother nature always cooperate? No.
You know

01:04:30.200 --> 01:04:32.910
going out and getting skunked is a big part
of it.

01:04:32.910 --> 01:04:36.369
That's why I went out and sat on a rock 14
hours. That's

01:04:36.369 --> 01:04:39.241
part of the process. When everything does
fall into place

01:04:39.241 --> 01:04:42.019
like you hope it will, then most of the time
my

01:04:42.019 --> 01:04:45.499
preconceived ideas of how I'm going to tell
a story will fall

01:04:45.499 --> 01:04:48.630
into place. That's what allows me to go up
a mountain

01:04:48.630 --> 01:04:50.789
with just the minimal camera gear I need to
get the

01:04:50.789 --> 01:04:54.039
job done for example because I don't walk
up the hill

01:04:54.039 --> 01:04:57.180
with a backpack full of gear. Not only does
it beat your

01:04:57.180 --> 01:04:59.519
down, but by the time you get up there, it's
so clumsy that

01:04:59.519 --> 01:05:02.160
you're probably going to scare something off.
So it's

01:05:02.160 --> 01:05:05.410
very much part of the process. At the same
time, solving

01:05:05.410 --> 01:05:07.369
problems is very much a part of photography.
You got to

01:05:07.369 --> 01:05:09.479
be able to do it.

01:05:09.479 --> 01:05:11.119
&gt;&gt; Male #7: The other question is which organization
have you

01:05:11.119 --> 01:05:15.719
found to be effective in helping us preserve
the wild

01:05:15.719 --> 01:05:16.719
heritage we have.

01:05:16.719 --> 01:05:20.739
&gt;&gt; Moose: Can we turn off the camera for a
second? I'm kidding.

01:05:20.739 --> 01:05:25.119
Be serious, very few. They all have a good
heart. But

01:05:25.119 --> 01:05:28.400
the word compromise is not in the system.
It's just not

01:05:28.400 --> 01:05:32.529
out there. And it's very disheartening. A
lot of times

01:05:32.529 --> 01:05:34.669
the information -- I work a lot behind the
scenes

01:05:34.669 --> 01:05:40.160
anymore. And it's very disheartening, because
no one can

01:05:40.160 --> 01:05:41.589
compromise. It's like I want to grab them
and go,

01:05:41.589 --> 01:05:45.250
do you realize things are
disappearing while you argue over this?”

01:05:45.250 --> 01:05:47.660
Seriously. We
can compromise. You don't have to lock everything

01:05:47.660 --> 01:05:50.289
up
behind walls. We don't have to bulldoze it

01:05:50.289 --> 01:05:54.459
all either.
There's a lot of avenues proven, you know,

01:05:54.459 --> 01:05:57.900
in the data
that would work. And compromise is difficult.

01:05:57.900 --> 01:06:00.369
Well, I
know it's getting around the time. I'll just

01:06:00.369 --> 01:06:02.099
leave you
with one last thing. I showed you some of

01:06:02.099 --> 01:06:06.689
my aviation
work, showed you some critters. I also do

01:06:06.689 --> 01:06:12.430
that thing called landscape
photography, which when you're out photographing

01:06:12.430 --> 01:06:15.309
critters, you can't help but see some of the
most amazing spots on

01:06:15.309 --> 01:06:18.919
this planet. And often we sit on a rock for
14 hours.

01:06:18.919 --> 01:06:22.079
Something good tends to happen out there.
And that's

01:06:22.079 --> 01:06:25.299
kind of what generates my landscape photography.
I just

01:06:25.299 --> 01:06:29.089
want to leave you one last note that you can
make a

01:06:29.089 --> 01:08:16.890
difference.

01:08:16.890 --> 01:10:04.680
[silence]

01:10:04.680 --> 01:11:52.480
&gt;[Applause]

